You are debugging a production issue where database modifications are silently committing, and unexpected database entries are persisted despite a downstream exception being thrown. A developer wrote the following Spring Boot service to handle payments:

java
@Service
public class PaymentService {
    @Autowired
    private OrderRepository orderRepository;

    public void processOrder(Order order) throws PaymentException {
        orderRepository.save(order);
        try {
            executePaymentGatewayCall(order);
        } catch (Exception e) {
            throw new PaymentException("Gateway failed", e);
        }
    }

    @Transactional(rollbackFor = PaymentException.class)
    public void executePaymentGatewayCall(Order order) throws PaymentException {
        if (order.getAmount() > 5000) {
            throw new PaymentException("Transaction limit exceeded");
        }
    }
}

When `order.getAmount()` is greater than 5000, `PaymentException` is successfully thrown and propagated, but the `Order` record remains persisted in the database.

You are debugging a production issue in an asynchronous distributed microservice. High-throughput distributed tracing logs are missing critical correlation metadata (like Trace IDs) inside asynchronous callback tasks, even though the trace context is fully populated in the main request thread. The developer configured the system as follows:

java
public CompletableFuture<Response> processAsync(Request request) {
    MDC.put("traceId", request.getTraceId());
    return CompletableFuture.supplyAsync(() -> {
        // Logging inside this block does not print the traceId!
        log.info("Processing request asynchronous payload");
        return gatewayService.call(request);
    }, customExecutor)
    .exceptionally(ex -> {
        // Logging inside this block also misses the traceId
        log.error("Asynchronous process failed", ex);
        return Response.fallback();
    });
}

You are debugging a production issue where an orchestration-based Saga coordinator fails to execute compensating actions. The saga is managed inside a transactional block. When downstream services fail, the coordinator attempts to catch the exception and execute compensation steps in the database, but those compensations throw an unexpected `UnexpectedRollbackException`:

java
@Transactional(propagation = Propagation.REQUIRED)
public void processSaga(SagaData data) {
    try {
        inventoryService.reserveInventory(data); // Under the hood, this throws an unchecked InventoryException
    } catch (InventoryException ex) {
        log.warn("Inventory reservation failed. Triggering compensation...");
        sagaRepository.updateStatus(data.getId(), SagaStatus.COMPENSATING); // This database write fails!
        paymentService.refund(data);
        throw ex;
    } 
}

Both `processSaga` and `inventoryService.reserveInventory` are annotated with `@Transactional(propagation = Propagation.REQUIRED)`. When `InventoryException` is thrown, the call to `sagaRepository.updateStatus` throws a transaction exception and cannot execute.
